{"title_page": "Aamir Bashir", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actor and film producer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = Aamir Bashir.jpg\n| name =Aamir Bashir\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Jammu and Kashmir (state)|Kashmir, India]]\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| notable role = \n}}\n'''Aamir Bashir''' (\u0906\u092e\u093f\u0930 \u092c\u0936\u0940\u0930) is an Indian actor and film producer.\n\n==About==\nAamir is an Indian director and producer best known for his powerful roles in ''A Wednesday'' and ''Haider''. After working in television shows and commercials, he made his feature acting debut in Dev Benegal's ''[[Split Wide Open]]''. He made his directorial and co-producer debut with ''Harud'', an Urdu film which won the National Award for the Best Urdu Feature Film at the 60th National Film Awards.\n\nWith over 14 feature films to his credit including ''Peepli (Live)'' and ''Gurgaon'', he was most recently seen in Netflix's first Indian Original series - [[Sacred Games (TV series)|''Sacred Games''.]]\n\nHe wrapped up shooting for [[Navdeep Singh (director)|Navdeep Singh's]] previously titled ''Hunter'' and now ''Laal Kaptaan,'' as well as the Amazon series ''Inside Edge''.\n\nHe is currently shooting the second season of ''Sacred Games'' and Balaji's next feature film.\n\n== Career ==\nHis acting career began with a very small role on television, in the ''Bhanwar'' TV series, and acted in several TV advertisements, this led to his film debut, ''[[Split Wide Open]]'' (1999) and the telefilm, ''Doordarshan Srinagar''.  He appeared in the 2003 film ''[[Armaan (2003 film)|Armaan]]''.<ref name=film>{{Cite web |url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/tv/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1658354 |title='Alpaviram' fame Aamir Bashir to do film on Kashmir |access-date=10 January 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208220421/http://entertainment.in.msn.com/tv/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1658354 |archive-date=8 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Acclaim came his way in 2008, with the thriller, ''[[A Wednesday]]'', where he played the role of a police inspector; the film also won him a [[Star Screen Awards|Screen Awards]] nomination for [[Star Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Actor in a Supporting Role]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2085856/awards Awards] [[IMDb]].</ref><ref>[http://inhome.rediff.com/movies/2008/sep/02bashir.htm Meet the cop in A Wednesday] [[Rediff.com]], 2 September 2008.</ref>\n\nBashir was set to play Shahrukh Khan's younger brother in the film ''[[My Name is Khan]]'', although things did not work out & was eventually replaced by [[Jimmy Sheirgill]] as Khan's younger brother.\n<ref name=bonding>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-06/news-interviews/28021127_1_lip-sync-songs-music-shah-rukh-khan |title=Karan's bonding with SRK & Kajol|last=Jha|first=Subhas K.|date=6 February 2009|accessdate=21 August 2009|work=The Times of India |location=India|publisher=[[The Times Group]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Bashir's directorial debut ''Harud'' premiered at the [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival]]. The film stars [[Reza Naji]] and Shahnawaz Bhat and takes place in [[Kashmir]].<ref name=\"life\">[http://www.hindu.com/mp/2008/09/06/stories/2008090653980700.htm Life after \u2018A Wednesday\u2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208193416/http://www.hindu.com/mp/2008/09/06/stories/2008090653980700.htm|date=8 February 2009}} [[The Hindu]], 6 September 2008.</ref><ref name=film/><ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Indian-films-crossover-to-Toronto/Article1-598182.aspx Indian films crossover to Toronto] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914204556/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Indian-films-crossover-to-Toronto/Article1-598182.aspx |date=14 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Actor===\n*''[[Inside Edge (TV series)|Inside Edge Season 2]]'' (2019)  - Bhaisahaab/Yashvardhan Patil\n*''[[Laal Kaptaan (film)|Laal Kaptaan]]'' (2019) - Adham Khan\n*''[[Sacred Games (TV series)|Sacred Games]]'' (2018) - Majid Khan\n*''[[Gurgaon (film)|Gurgaon]]'' (2017) - Bhupi\n*''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' (2014)\n*''Future To Bright Hai Ji'' (2012) - Ajay Kumar\n*''[[Peepli Live]]'' (2010) - Vivek\n*''[[Raat Gayi Baat Gayi]]'' (2009) - Prasad\n*''[[A Wednesday]]'' (2008) - Jai Pratap Singh - PI\n*''[[The Great Indian Butterfly]]'' (2007) - Krish\n*''[[Frozen (2007 film)|Frozen]]'' (2007) - Commanding Officer\n*''[[Pyaar Ke Side Effects]]'' (2006) -  Kapil Sharma\n* ''[[Rishtey (TV series)|Rishtey]]'' (TV series)  \"[[List of Rishtey episodes (Season 1)|Sirf Tum\" Season 1]]\n* ''[[Isse Kehte Hai Golmaal Ghar]]'' (TV Series) 2004\n*''[[Armaan (2003 film)|Armaan]]'' (2003) -  Dr. Sanjay\n* ''[[Sarhadein]]'' (TV series) (2002)\n* ''Clever and Lonely'' (2002) - Aditya\n*''[[Split Wide Open]]'' (1999) - The Husband\n*''[[Alpviram]]'' (TV series) (1998)\n*''[[Antaral]]'' (TV series) (2000)\n\n===Director===\n*''[[Harud]]'' (2010)\n\n==Awards==\n* [[60th National Film Awards|2012]]: [[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]] for [[Discontinued and Intermittent National Film Awards#Best Feature Film in Urdu|Best Feature Film in Urdu]]: ''Harud''<ref name=\"60thaward\">{{cite press_release|title=60th National Film Awards Announced|url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2013/mar/d2013031801.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB), India|accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Aamir Bashir}}\n*{{IMDb name|2085856}}\n*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-09-03/news-interviews/27943429_1_jackie-chan-aamir-bashir-naseeruddin-shah \"Why Aamir Bashir was taken aback\"] - ''[[The Times of India]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bashir, Aamir}}\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:St. Stephen's College, Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actor and film producer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = Aamir Bashir.jpg\n| name =Aamir Bashir\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Jammu and Kashmir (state)|Kashmir, India]]\n| occupation = [[Actor]]\n| notable role = \n}}\n'''Aamir Bashir''' (\u0906\u092e\u093f\u0930 \u092c\u0936\u0940\u0930) is an Indian actor and film producer\n\n==About==\nAamir is an Indian director and producer best known for his powerful roles in ''A Wednesday'' and ''Haider''. After working in television shows and commercials, he made his feature acting debut in Dev Benegal's ''[[Split Wide Open]]''. He made his directorial and co-producer debut with [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_nVJLQIAQYk ''Harud''], an Urdu film which won the National Award for the Best Urdu Feature Film at the 60th National Film Awards.\n\nWith over 14 feature films to his credit including ''Peepli (Live)'' and ''Gurgaon'', he was most recently seen in Netflix's first Indian Original series - [[Sacred Games (TV series)|''Sacred Games''.]]\n\nHe wrapped up shooting for [[Navdeep Singh (director)|Navdeep Singh's]] previously titled ''Hunter'' and now ''Laal Kaptaan,'' as well as the Amazon series ''Inside Edge''.\n\nHe is currently shooting the second season of ''Sacred Games'' and Balaji's next feature film.\n\n== Career ==\nHis acting career began with a very small role on television, in the ''Bhanwar'' TV series, and acted in several TV advertisements, this led to his film debut, ''[[Split Wide Open]]'' (1999) and the telefilm, ''Doordarshan Srinagar''.  He appeared in the 2003 film ''[[Armaan (2003 film)|Armaan]]''.<ref name=film>{{Cite web |url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/tv/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1658354 |title='Alpaviram' fame Aamir Bashir to do film on Kashmir |access-date=10 January 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208220421/http://entertainment.in.msn.com/tv/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1658354 |archive-date=8 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Acclaim came his way in 2008, with the thriller, ''[[A Wednesday]]'', where he played the role of a police inspector; the film also won him a [[Star Screen Awards|Screen Awards]] nomination for [[Star Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Actor in a Supporting Role]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2085856/awards Awards] [[IMDb]].</ref><ref>[http://inhome.rediff.com/movies/2008/sep/02bashir.htm Meet the cop in A Wednesday] [[Rediff.com]], 2 September 2008.</ref>\n\nBashir was set to play Shahrukh Khan's younger brother in the film ''[[My Name is Khan]]'', although things did not work out & was eventually replaced by [[Jimmy Sheirgill]] as Khan's younger brother.\n<ref name=bonding>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-06/news-interviews/28021127_1_lip-sync-songs-music-shah-rukh-khan |title=Karan's bonding with SRK & Kajol|last=Jha|first=Subhas K.|date=6 February 2009|accessdate=21 August 2009|work=The Times of India |location=India|publisher=[[The Times Group]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Bashir's directorial debut ''Harud'' premiered at the [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival]]. The film stars [[Reza Naji]] and Shahnawaz Bhat and takes place in [[Kashmir]].<ref name=\"life\">[http://www.hindu.com/mp/2008/09/06/stories/2008090653980700.htm Life after \u2018A Wednesday\u2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208193416/http://www.hindu.com/mp/2008/09/06/stories/2008090653980700.htm|date=8 February 2009}} [[The Hindu]], 6 September 2008.</ref><ref name=film/><ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Indian-films-crossover-to-Toronto/Article1-598182.aspx Indian films crossover to Toronto] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914204556/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Indian-films-crossover-to-Toronto/Article1-598182.aspx |date=14 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Actor===\n*''[[Inside Edge (TV series)|Inside Edge Season 2]]'' (2019)  - Bhaisahaab/Yashvardhan Patil\n*''[[Laal Kaptaan (film)|Laal Kaptaan]]'' (2019) - Adham Khan\n*''[[Sacred Games (TV series)|Sacred Games]]'' (2018) - Majid Khan\n*''[[Gurgaon (film)|Gurgaon]]'' (2017) - Bhupi\n*''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' (2014)\n*''Future To Bright Hai Ji'' (2012) - Ajay Kumar\n*''[[Peepli Live]]'' (2010) - Vivek\n*''[[Raat Gayi Baat Gayi]]'' (2009) - Prasad\n*''[[A Wednesday]]'' (2008) - Jai Pratap Singh - PI\n*''[[The Great Indian Butterfly]]'' (2007) - Krish\n*''[[Frozen (2007 film)|Frozen]]'' (2007) - Commanding Officer\n*''[[Pyaar Ke Side Effects]]'' (2006) -  Kapil Sharma\n* ''[[Rishtey (TV series)|Rishtey]]'' (TV series)  \"[[List of Rishtey episodes (Season 1)|Sirf Tum\" Season 1]]\n* ''[[Isse Kehte Hai Golmaal Ghar]]'' (TV Series) 2004\n*''[[Armaan (2003 film)|Armaan]]'' (2003) -  Dr. Sanjay\n* ''[[Sarhadein]]'' (TV series) (2002)\n* ''Clever and Lonely'' (2002) - Aditya\n*''[[Split Wide Open]]'' (1999) - The Husband\n*''[[Alpviram]]'' (TV series) (1998)\n*''[[Antaral]]'' (TV series) (2000)\n\n===Director===\n*''[[Harud]]'' (2010)\n\n==Awards==\n* [[60th National Film Awards|2012]]: [[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]] for [[Discontinued and Intermittent National Film Awards#Best Feature Film in Urdu|Best Feature Film in Urdu]]: ''Harud''<ref name=\"60thaward\">{{cite press_release|title=60th National Film Awards Announced|url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2013/mar/d2013031801.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB), India|accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Aamir 